text:
¬†@ninjaofcake¬† I worked with the police (don't ask me where) as an IT engineer in a case of children abductions. The investigation was long, I was there for support in case they needed to hack into certain computers and networks.
The thing is, there was a group of delinquents taking children up to 12 years and killing them for their corneas, eyes in general and maybe some other organ. This was done by request of rich people that needed those things for them.

The children weren't even spared after this, they were killed. I had to go into those facilities and the sight was disgusting, sad, heartbreaking. Corpses of kids laying around a some kind of stone table. Big containers with organs that they didn't need. Children with their thorax opened. Some dismembered. Flies all over the place. That putrid smell that you can't just get used to. Some corpses showing signs of torture.

I tried to avoid looking as much as I could, but it was nearly impossible. The criminals were killed in that operation. The commandant gave that order even though the team was ordered to capture them alive.

If you were there with me, you would not even flinch at this game gore scenes. I still remember that and still feel sad and impotent at this kind of thing happening to innocent kids.
author: @Syokool

text:
¬†@Syokool¬† Mad respect. Thank you for your service and all that you do. You may or may not be lying, but that‚Äôs not what matters. Your brief description helped me vividly imagine the scenes that you described, although I‚Äôm certain that what I imagined wasn‚Äôt even 1/10th of what you saw with your own two eyes.  

Once again, I‚Äôm really thankful for you and the others, who help shed light and expose these kind of things. They hardly get covered on the internet, but I‚Äôm sure they happen everywhere, perhaps even as I‚Äôm typing this message. 

Unfortunately, there‚Äôs always a bad if there‚Äôs ever a good. After all, you can never distinguish light if you never experienced darkness. It‚Äôs truly saddening that these things happen, but that‚Äôs the harsh reality. On a last note, I‚Äôd like to thank you once again for your work. Stay safe.

text: ¬†@ilovetrash2131¬† It does have decent atmosphere, but not well implemented enough to be that memorable to me personally.
